title: A basic, but fun little mouse that is absolutely worth it
text: How much should a computer mouse cost? If I was asked this question a week ago, I'd probably estimate about $10-$15 for a basic mouse, and I could even imagine $20-$30 (or even more) for a super fancy, 20-button, ergonomic, ultra-responsive space mouse. At the time of this review, this mouse is $5. That price would be understandable if this was one of those old school non-optical, trackball mice (with the ball at the bottom). But this mouse is sleek...it's rechargeable (via included micro-USB...though I would prefer if it was the more popular USB-C)...it can be connected with Bluetooth or USB receiver (I've tried both, and they are responsive and without issues, so far)...it changes LED colors...and it's silent. Admittedly, this is not a particularly high-end mouse. For example, there is no forward-back option, there are no programming buttons, it's not shaped with the ergonomic curves, and the scroll wheel is not textured (which I prefer over a smooth one). This mouse is an attractive matte color, it is very portable/low-height, it has 3 DPI levels (nothing too sensitive, but more than adequate for my needs), and both the left and right click buttons are fairly quiet. Functionally, it glides smoothly on my Roccat mousepad, and I have had no issues with connectivity yet. In all honesty, despite the shortcomings, I really appreciate this mouse, and for the price, it is an absolute bargain.

title: Overkill for what I am doing, but why not!
text: I had a set of the ZenWifi XT8s (Triband Wifi 6 = no 6ghz). Got this to boost wifi in the house AND get the 10gbe ports for LAN use. (Streaming from a NAS, etc.). It's overkill, but I wanted to transfer files fast. I followed DongKnowsTech dot com and had the Mesh setup pretty quickly. Did have to restart everything a few times, but no biggie. Upgraded firmware to latest and set up network. Everything is working fine, EXCEPT the 10gbe ports seem finnicky. To be more specific, they seem to slow down over time. I can reboot the router, and get 950mbps, but after awhile, it will drop to 800, then 650, etc. This is WAN btw. I really have not test LAN speed, but appears to be pretty quick. A quick reboot of the router fixes the issue temporarily. I installed the latest Merlin firmware, and the issue seems to persist. I am thinking this will be fixed in a future firmware release, but who knows. Frankly, however, there is no real world difference between 600 mbps and 900. They are both plenty fast. You do want to get what you are paying your ISP for though. Wifi is great, even though we only have one device (a laptop) in the house capable of 6ghz (Wifi 6e). Otherwise, the main purpose of this (for me) is the Multi-gigabit LAN capability and AiMesh compatability. I have this paired with a TRENDnet TEG-S762 10g switch to feed the AiMesh nodes at 2.5g.  All cables are Cat 8 (supposedly). Overall, a very powerful router, although expensive. I feel it should serve my purposes for 5-7 years before everything is switched over to Wifi 7.

title: Issue with getting Motorola product support
text:
Unit was very easy to install and set up. I have had this unit for approx. 4 months. Was working very well until the last 3 weeks. We started dropping the internet signal intermittently . It would reboot automatically. I contacted Xfinity about this issue since they are my provider. They were very good about trying to fix the issue. They installed a signal monitor for several days and found that it was a problem with this modem. It has a 2 year warranty through Motorola. At this time I am having some difficulty reaching them for support. Hopefully it will get replaced.

Wanted to add some info: I had contact with motorola support. I had to send them reports from the modem. They told me that some of my bonded channels had too much power and was out of range for the modem. my internet provider had been to my residence and placed a signal monitor on for a few days after checking that all connections were good. It showed that the signals and power levels were all within their parameters. My xfinity tech sent me the report which I sent to the motorola tech. I was wanting them to replace it and I would try another unit but now I am just stuck with the Motorola tech saying that their equipment is fine. In my opinion, the motorola equipment is built with too tight of tolerances. They really don't stand behind their product. I was asked for an opinion about the service I received from Motorola. I explained everything that I have laid out here and have received no response.
Just thought I would put this out there so everyone else would know. Buyer beware. I will now have to look for another modem since this one just keeps dropping at random.

text:

title: Works well; great value for the price!
text:
I use this to share a monitor between a Linux machine and two windows machines. It works well, but shoves everything onto the machine's second monitor (if you have one) when you switch away, and it takes a couple of seconds to rearrange the windows when switching back. In addition to keyboard/mouse and video, HDMI sound and my 3DConnexion 3D mouse all switch perfectly..
Only complaint is that waking from sleep using the keyboard only seems to work on the last computer you put to sleep; the others need to be awakened with the power switch on the computer.

title: Mixed feelings
text:
I have had the first generation, as well as the second generation fire TV cube. I was very excited to purchase the third generation.

After having use this product for about a month, I would not recommend upgrading if you already have a second generation. The reason for this is that I am not seen any performance improvement. The addition of a USB port is nice, but is USB 2.0 and this is highly disappointing. The HDMI input may have some nice applications for people, but it does not provide value for me. The ethernet addition is also nice but 100 Mbps is also highly disappointing. Modern Wi-Fi provides far faster speeds.

There is another strange thing occurring with my Sony XBR TV around power management that was not occurring with the prior generations. This is one of the more frustrating issues. The device control with the third generation based on my experience is worse than prior generations.

I considered returning the device and probably should have, but I will continue to use it with an open mind. It would have been nice to have seen a thunderbolt port and gigabit ethernet. It is highly surprising that such old technology are the added upgrades.

***Adding to this review with great disappointment in regard to Amazon's trade in policy. I have chosen to return the FireTV cube. I would regret holding onto the device due to its mediocrity. Amazon does not permit the reuse of the trade in value or provide any recuperation of the value of the trade in. I will be -1 device at the completion of the return. I do not feel this is a customer first position and conflicts with Amazon's first and most important leadership principle, Customer Obsession.

https://www.amazon.jobs/content/en/our-workplace/leadership-principles

Live and learn :(

title: So fun to use. Impressive zoom
text:
This is so fun. I cannot believe the things I am able to see, and how close up I can get to them.

The attachment is really well thought out allowing me to attach and look through any of the lenses on my iPhone 13 Max Pro. The mini tripod is also extremely handy. I use this constantly even when not using the monocular.

One of the coolest things I noticed about this was when I was filming in a heavily wooded area. I was able to zoom in on a squirrel and must have been 200ft away, and then also zoom out, and focus in on a spider web between the trees that was about 30 feet in front if me. The spider web had enough detail where I could make out the dew on it.

Another really cool thing I did with this is zoomed into the clouds. They seemed impossibly far away, but looking back at the footage I was able to see a bird soaring around up there that wasnt even visible to my naked eye.

One thing I will say though, is that this seemed to perform better when filming under the trees in the shade. When I brought it out to the beach, it still filmed very nicely, but it was better with the sun to my bad. I think if the sun hits the lens directly it can cause some extra colors, or unwanted effects.

This is very fun for just messing around, but could also go a very long way with a nice tripod too.

title: Robust, NFC Sort of Works
text:
Feitian comes in a sealed package which, if you are careful, can be reclosed in case it is for backup in a file drawer. I have this Feitian FIDO NFC as well as an NFC black YubiKey (+ another non-NFC white YubiKey). However, trying to add either security key to ANY account on my phone by NFC was a complete failure. Who knows why?

Google accepted BOTH the Feitian FIDO and my NFC YubiKey using USB (on my computer). However, Google refused the non-NFC white YubiKey. Who knows why? Once setup, it now accepts the Feitian FIDO key using NFC on my Samsung phone. Hooray!!

Microsoft accepted the Feitian FIDO using USB but required that I set an associated pin (which I had to carefully write down). It rejected BOTH YubiKeys. Who knows why?

Bitwarden accepted the Feitian FIDO AND both YubiKeys using USB. Why does setting up security keys need to be such a mystery?

title: Nice camera and screen but proprietary connections all around
text:
This kit is designed to give you a camera for your car or truck when you don't have a built-in screen.

The camera mounts to standard license plate holes (once you figure out how to run a wire into the trunk). There are white "night vision" LEDs attached to the camera and they turn on and off automatically based on the brightness. The camera image is clear and colorful, obviously don't expect HD quality.

The screen is a variant of the ubiquitous mini LCDs you can find. It's decently clear and has some settings to configure the image, including the usual brightness/contrast and several mirror/flip settings which you would need depending on which way you face the included camera. There is a windshield suction cup mount as well as a screw-on mount provided in the box.

Connections between the screen and camera are proprietary. They look similar to connections provided with other cameras but there doesn't seem to be a standard for these 4-pin "micro DIN" connectors. This unfortunately makes the screen useless without the included camera. If you're thinking about wiring this up to some other video source, it won't work. The buttons on the screen allow switching between "video 1" and "video 2" but there is no way to connect a second video source.

title: It does work for a webcam or phone, but nothing more.
text:
[[VIDEOID:ec7d1d65cbc6791aaf3d7cab80e8655a]] To call it junk would be an understatement. The aluminum tubes are crimped on to the plastic joints with just a couple of 1mm indentations. The fit is is quite loose and wobbly, even without any weight on it. The claim that it can hold 6.6lbs is a joke. I put my A7ii with a 58mm lens on it and nearly broke it. I had even taken out the middle arm section hoping to improve stiffness.

Overall, not recommended...not even for a webcam.

title: Fragile, cheap cord-DO NOT BUY unless you want a lot of daily headaches.
text:
This hub still works 5 months later, but the cord is very fragile And touchy. If i bump my tablet or setting something down on the desk, it resets the connection, which doesn't always come back with out some serious tinkering with to get to send a signal to my tablet.

essentially, the cable is damaged from practically nothing but being plugged into he side of my tablet (in landscape) while it is sitting on a stand at a 45 degree angle. It's own weight is too much for the cable. I eventually had to add a 90 usb-c adapter the kind that points either up or down , not in parallel to the tablet.This makes it somewhat useful but I have to adjust it multiple times per day. I am certain it won't last much longer. I wish I had either purchased a more reliable brand or a short type-c extension cord so the weight of the device itself didn't damage the internal connections with the cable. And yes, I have tested the port on my tablet. It is in perfect working conditon with other usb-type devices and cables connected to it. It's just the incredibly stiff yet poorly made cable that connects the hub to your device.

title: AX 90 6600
text: It was time....Had an AC1750 for years.  Great upgrade. Noticeable and immediate improvement.  No longer need the extenders in our 2400sq foot single story home.  Strong download speeds and signal throughout. I have it placed in the front corner wall of the house and still have a signal throughout our entire 1/2 acre lot and 300+ feet down the street.  We're not gamers and just two of us in the house, but generally have 15-20 devices running on the router and streaming up to 4 TV's at a time.  I also have a VoiP phone plugged in for work.  We work from home and we're on video calls much of the day.  We're on the cheap spectrum 500mbps/20mbps plan and we get close to 600 download and 23+ upload....That maybe partially due to the fact Google fiber is now in the neighborhood and spectrum needs to stay competitive.  Easy setup.  Like the ease of turning on/off the guest network when needed.  Had an issue with one of the many laptops continuing to connect to the 2.4 network but turned out just needed to reset the laptop driver.  I like the tether app for most settings, but just be aware there are some other sophisticated settings you need to log into network to set/adjust.  I imagine we'll grow into this for years to come and works good for our lifestyle.  Glad I bought it when it was only $200

title: Good Hub
text:
Ordered this hub to use as a laptop dock. I have my keyboard, mouse, power, and external monitor plugged into it. When I'm using my laptop at the desk, all I have to do is plug the USB-C cable into it, and I'm ready to go! No more plugging in each device separately, and it has allowed me to clean up the cables and zip tie them together, since I don't need to move them separately.

I did also plug my Samsung phone into it and could use Dex with the keyboard, mouse, and monitor. I don't use Dex a lot, but it's cool to know that it works with this, so I can use it as a dock for that as well.

It works so well, that in hindsight, I wish I would have gotten the 14 in 1 version, since that one includes an ethernet port. My laptop has WiFi, of course, but when I'm using it at my desk I wish I would have upgraded to have the faster internet that I can get over ethernet vs. WiFi. Not a knock on the product at all -- just passing along my situation in case others might have the same situation and should consider getting the one with more options.

title: Impressed
text:
I recently purchased the Portable Projector because I like camping and I am extremely impressed with its performance. The compact size and lightweight design make it easy to take with me on camping trips, and the picture quality is fantastic. I tried it this week and it was beyond great, even when projected on a large outdoor screen.

One of the things I liked the most about this projector is its versatility. I used it for outdoor with my family and I also tried it in my living room. Well worth the cost.

title: Good middle ground video head
text: I like this tripod head for video work on my Nikon Z cameras. I am using it for a Z7II with a 5.5 inch monitor in the hot shoe and the Sigma 50-100 F1.8, which is a pretty heavy lens. title: Light and bright
text:
These earbuds are a little different than most in that they attach to the outer edge of your ear. There isn't an actual clip to hold them in place but just a flexible rubber hook. I think they are very comfortable, light weight, and they stay attached pretty well, probably due to their light weight and small size. The web page says they are for small ear canals but they are open ear phones so nothing really goes into your ear except the music. There is no adjustment for the positioning of the earbuds and since everyone has different sized ears the speakers may or may not line up with your ear canals. In my case they don't but I can compensate by increasing the volume.

The sound is very bright and clear which is great but they are almost too bright. I had to use the treble reduction setting on the EQ in my iPhone. I think they sound good but there is minimal bass response.

Sometimes when I try to adjust their position I end up touching the control functions and the music stops. Also a couple of times when I took them out of the case only one earbud connected with my phone. I was able to re-connect both earbuds eventually by touching the controls on the earbuds. I almost think it would be easier to just control the earbuds with my phone.

Overall I am pleased with these earbuds except for the issues I mentioned.

title: 6 years later.. outlasted Alienware!
text: Purchased Dec. 2016, powered up and turned on 24/7/365 with an Alienware 18" laptop, 50"/55" LED TV, Roku Ultra/Pro, WiFi router, & 10" 100W powered subwoofer, all plugged into the battery backup side only. Throughout the years the 50" TV was upgraded to 55", the Roku Ultra became a Roku Pro Soundbar, several WiFi router changes, and the Alienware laptop died! The Cyberpower kept going. It let me watch movies on the TV with the subwoofer on and volume way up during blackouts. It protected my pricy gear and kept my peace of mind while watching the lights flicker during storms. Did I mention it outlasted my OG Alienware 18?! The laptops hard drive failed and operating system became obsolete, before I ever had to change my first Cyberpower battery. I now own four (4) of these beautiful backups. They power all my expensive stuff. Even have one just for the built-in KitchenAid refrigerator. And very thankful for the one powering my 16 camera PoE security system during the last power outage. When a neighbor kid decided to take advantage and do some prowling for ebikes.

title: Meh.. I still prefer my Remarkable2
text:
I was very excited when I saw that Kindle was coming out with an E Ink Tablet. I have been using my Remarkable2 tablet for several years and absolutely love it. The one feature I wish it had was to download my books. I suppose you can on the Remarkable2 but it‚Äôs a lot of trouble and as far as I know doesn‚Äôt support kindle.
Anyway, I preordered this back in September and received it a week before Christmas. I already have a bad taste in my mouth due to the price drop and not being refunded the difference but I digress.

I do like the bigger Kindle screen however it‚Äôs a little too cumbersome to travel with. I like to throw my kindle in my purse or my bag so I can read while I‚Äôm waiting for appointments or on my lunch break. The scribe is too big for that or at least in my opinion.

My heartache comes from the notebook itself. My remarkable allows me to create multiple folders and notebooks, so far I haven‚Äôt found that feature on Kindle. It writes ok, but I wish there were more options for the type of pen I wanted to use. Remarkable has a highlighter, calligraphy, pencil, thin, medium and thick options. Kindle scribe is very limited.
I was hoping that Kindle would give us the option to make notes right on the page but it doesn‚Äôt, you have to create a sticky note and then it saves the notes to a separate book in your library. Which is fine I guess but if I download a workbook, I would like to have the option to write on those pages instead of having to continue to make notes on a separate page.
To sum it up, I won‚Äôt return this because I do like the bigger screen for reading but I‚Äôm also having a bit of buyers remorse. If you are looking for an E Ink tablet to replace paper then spend the hundred extra dollars or so and buy the Remarkable2.
Hopefully Amazon is reading these reviews and will take note when doing a software upgrade.

Love these and recommend them for anyone looking for a reasonably priced set of wireless ear buds!

title: A good little kit for hiding wires in a wall
text:
I ordered this to run a few cables behind the wall in my son's room for his TV. This kit was perfect for this as it comes with the hole covers and the tool to cut a nice circular hole in the drywall to pass the wires/cables thru. The hole covers are a 2 piece design that allow the inner part to anchor itself to the wall and then press the visible cover part into it for a nice a clean look.

My only issues where this: #1- The covers have a smell to them that take a while to dissipate and it's not a nice smell at all. #2- the hole saw bit was for a drill with a chuck and all my drills are a hex quick release. So I had to barrow an old corded drill with a standard chuck bit in order to even use this. (This is why I took away 1 star overall on the review.)

Overall, I still think this is a good little kit but I would change the above mentioned issues to make it an even better kit.

title: Pleasant Surprise
text:
I got this laptop second hand off here. It was advertised as having a 6th Gen Intel Core i7 processor but... turns out it had a 7th Gen Intel Core i7 instead. That was nice. Also, even though this isn't a gaming PC by today's standards, it did have a 2GB dedicates nvidia graphics card built in. Couldn't tell because the laptop had a skin on it. But found out when I started it up. SSD makes this the quickest starting PC I've ever owned.

I use it for light gaming, light sound and video editing. Nothing too taxing.

But I did notice the slight step down from using a 1080p resolution panel on my 17inch HP envy to this 14inch 720p one. But solid build.

title: Great motherboard
text:
Great motherboard for my i7 13th gen build. No CPU overclocking can be done. I am not using it for gaming but I run some CPU intensive applications. So far so good. Comes with 3 x 5V RGB terminals and they are perfect for my RGB fans. Inbuilt wifi gives about 300Mbps throughput. I really love the PCIE Q release and the M2 Q-latch features. Only downside is to install a NVME drive in the M2 slot 2 or 3, I had to remove the graphics card installed in the nearby PCIE slot.
Configuration:
Intel core i7 13700K
32GB TEAMGROUP DDR4 3600Mhz
2TB NVME
Vetroo V360 Liquid CPU Cooler
Corsair iCUE 4000X case
Corsair RM750e modular power supply
GTX 1070 Graphics(OLD)

title: DDJ Waterproof Airtag Holder Review
text:

Pros:

Waterproof design
Full body anti-scratch protection
Fits Airtags securely
Comes in multiple colors
Cons:

Only comes in pack of 4
May not fit all dog collar sizes
Compared to similar products in the market, the DDJ Waterproof Airtag Holder stands out for its durability and waterproof feature. It is also more affordable than some of its competitors, which is a plus.

Overall, I highly recommend the DDJ Waterproof Airtag Holder for anyone looking for a reliable and stylish way to protect their Airtag. Its sturdy design and waterproof feature make it an excellent investment for pet owners, travelers, and anyone who wants to keep their keys organized.

title: One of the best prelubed switch options
text:
Just to provide some more context on these switches:

These are clearly Haimu-made switches using their customary Nylon blend for both the top and bottom housing, and their POM blend for the stems. The factory prelube for a lot of these Haimu switches and other such as the Zuoce Rococo, the Haimu x Geon switches, and the Moondrop switches is pretty solid and smooth, and they're one of the few prelubed switches that are basically good to go right out of the box. The Browns here are NOT a light tactile but more of a med-heavy tactile, and all of Haimu's tactiles have a relatively sharper P-shaped bump rather than a longer D-shaped bump. Haimu's plastic blend also gives their switches a higher pitched sound profile in comparison to a lot of other switches. Finally, since these are Haimus, the silent Linear and Silent Tactiles here also have their slotted stem leg design and holes in the bottom housing to minimize the sound. These can also be found on the Haimu Heartbeat and Whisper switches. I mention all of this to basically note that Haimu is kinda a one-trick pony right now, but the trick is a very good one. Pick your Haimu switches based on things like spring weighting, accessibility (these being on Amazon with Prime shipping makes them super accessible), maybe even color scheme, whatever. But know that for the most part, any Haimu switch you get is going to have similar sound profiles and similar stock smoothness. Hope this helps!

title: NIce idea, strangely executed
text:
This is expected to be a hit with those magnetic plugs and how you connect your phones, tablets and other devices. What bothers me very much is how this cable works, it shows 1 hour 40 minutes to the full charge on the phone, then after a minute it shows 9 hours, then suddenly 6 hours. When another phone connected to this cable and some app is running it actually doesn't charge, because the power consumption is more than power supply of the charge. I checked the same phone and same charges with another cable (regular, non magnetic USB-C) and it does charge the phone when the app is running.
My verdict the cable is poorly made and the charge which flows through it is unstable to say the least.

title: Good wireless headset little over dialed in highs
text:
I have the TH10 so I thought I would try these TH11. I was thinking they were the better of the two because of the higher number. But actually these have a 40mm speaker and the TH10 has a 50mm speaker.

Thankfully they both sound basically identical which is odd. Notice I said thankfully. That's because the TH10s headset is a bit tight on my head. Whereas these TH11 have less tight hold and around the ears they have more cushion and it's much softer. So even though these have 10mm smaller speakers I think I'll use these since they sound the same.

Just like the other model this Bluetooth tv headset comes with plenty of options to hook it up. And set up is very easy. It is very much plug and play.

I am pretty sure both the TH10 and TH11 use the exact same transmitter box. That's not a bad thing because the transmitter works flawlessly. No static or drop outs. And the range is excellent. I can walk to the kitchen, bathroom, all over and keep the signal.

The reason for four stars instead of five is only because these like the other model have the highs dialed in a little to much. I have another brand that has small in-ear earbuds and they seem to have more bass and the highs are more balanced. But these work perfectly fine. And I feel over ear headphones are a bit healthier for the ears then having ear buds plugged down in them every night. Tuning the bass and treble where you like can be done with the tv or a receiver.

title: Really nice, powerful small computer
text:
I've been on the search for a computer I can use as an emulation device hooked up to my TV. This one pretty much perfectly fits that need.

Packaging is very plain but the computer is well-packed. You get a power cord, mounting hardware and an HDMI cable.

Setup is a piece of cake, just power it up, finish the Windows registration stuff and you're off and running. There's minimal bloatware installed - basically none.

Performance is terrific. The 16 gigs of RAM really helps and you've also got an NVME drive so everything feels very responsive.

For gameplay, this works well for emulation. Everything up through Dreamcast is a piece of cake. Beyond that, it's a little hit and miss. With the lack of dedicated graphics hardware, don't expect to play PS3 games or AAA titles through Steam or the like. Just not going to happen.

My only gripe is the Wifi. Absolutely could not get it to connect at top speeds to my router. Tried everything and just could not. That stunk but is not a huge dealbreaker for my use case. Your mileage might vary.

Overall, this is an excellent computer that can handle pretty much everything you throw at it outside of modern games. It's quiet, powerful, has lots of RAM, lots of disk drive space (1 TB) and works great. Perhaps a touch overpriced but a solid device nonetheless.

title: This is a MUST HAVE!
text:
I can't believe the amount of thought that must have gone into this design. It has a 6000mAh rechargable battery (external cord included) that can power the radio for up to 42 hours or the built in lights for up to 16 hours, OR recharge external devices (phones, tablets, etc). It includes built in lightening cable, USB A, mini USB, and USB C. The built in USB C cable can also be used to recharge the battery if you don't have the external cable handy. The battery piwer level is indicated by blue lights at 25% intervals.
If the rechargeable battery is dead, the crank can be used to power the battery, even for recharging external devices! Of course it can also power the AM/FM/WB radio or the flashlight or reading light. It also has an 80dB SOS alarm.
The flashlight is a superbright LED, and it has a flip up LED reading light. This is indispensable in any emergency or limited power availability situation.

title: It was great while it worked!
text:
Very excited to have a projector, as expected, it doesn't perform great in lit rooms. But the sound and picture quality are good in dark rooms. Unfortunately after one use of screen mirroring on android, the entire screen mirroring menu as well as the wifi menu stopped working, with only a white popup coming up for a split second.

The device still performs with HDMI cable, which is our method now. as well as on IOS, HOWEVER; the ios screen mirroring seems to be counter productive, requiring to be connected to the device via WIFI, rendering the entire screen mirroring system as an OFFLINE only screen mirroring. This was not the case with android.

Our mistake was going on a 5g wifi network when we did the one time screen mirroring on android. so avoid that and you'll be smooth sailing!!

title: Tripp Lite TLP808B 8 Outlet Surge Protector Power
text:
My entertainment surge protector was a Belkin Pure AV bought back in the Buy.com days and now part of bar controled by trip switch will not power on anymore so time for replacement. Don't need coaxail, phone, dsl protection never have used them and always been fine. USB protection for a AV surge protector doesn't make sense since everything will have a power plug and pretty much not going to need continuing access to it anyway. The spec's looked good and like unused plugs have built in cover to keep dust and other contaminants out. My TV cost less than $350 4 years ago along with Vizio sound bar which was around $150 so why buy expensive surge protector anymore. This looked like it will do the job and way smaller than my older one so going to give it a try. This is something you hope never gets put to the test.
Update: hooked it up today and so far ok, all check lights lit and devices powering up. TV picture is clean no noticeable interference and sound bar has no unwanted background noise so guessing will be fine. title: Well built, works as advertised
text:
The device appears to be well built. The instructions are not very clear but the operation is fairly obvious. One thing not mentioned in the ad is that the module outputs a roughly square wave which is the digital version of the Doppler signal. It is unsuitable to directly drive a relay. You need a one-shot or the digital equivalent using a micro controller if you want to drive a relay. On the other hand, by measuring the frequency of the signal, you get an idea of how fast the object is approaching or going away.

The antenna pattern is not omnidirectional. The beam is narrower in the plane of the longest dimension. But I found that sensitivity is still good at almost 90 degrees from the main axis of the sensor (I was detected at 10-15 feet coming off the side when adjusted to the highest sensitivity), so that may be enough for many applications.

I like that it has 4 mounting holes and comes with the connector and wire harness and LED indicators.

title: Pros and cons
text:
I was planning to buy this Echo for ages because I though the screen was a good tool for many things.

After a couple of months trying it:

Pros:

Good design
Good image and display
Good size for my needs (previously I wanted to buy the Echo Show 8, but with the 5 is more than enough)
Good sound

Big cons:

The microphone is terrible! sometimes I need to scream so the device can answer me. I though it was something about the Spanish configuration (even though I am a Spanish native speaker), but I changed it to english and it was the same problem. After a few days, I "tried" manually to turn off the mic and turn it on and it helped, but it is annoying to do it every time the device is not answering (many times a day). I had an echo 1st generation and sometimes even just whispering, the device could hear me and I thought that doing this big change, would be surreal, far from reality.

Overall, if you just need the screen to make it "cooler", it is good, but the mic problem can be frustrating sometimes.

title: Very solid board.
text:
The MSI z790i is probably the best ITX Z board money can buy. It helps overclocking your cpu and ram really well. The shortcuts to UV and OC are really handy especially for those less technologically saavy and want the best efficiency or performance with a few clicks. There is a small fan and it is not obnoxious like other motherboards. The temps for components on the board are well within spec and the worst is the PCH usually in the 60s and 70s. I definitely recommend this board over the ROG strix z790 due to the daughterboard issues, the clunky hive module many do not like and the price of it is clearly not competitive for the features presented. OTOH the MSI z790i is priced very nice and will get you going where you need to go quick.

If I had one gripe with this board is I wished the connections were placed different or at least a little more easily accessible. ITX boards can be challenging in a SFF build and say having all the fan headers placed close together AND in a spot where it's easy to reach all 3 would have been much nicer but that is the price paid for ITX. Also, XMP has had no problems or hiccups whatsoever. Once trained boot is quick especially if you're using a high quality gen 4 drive. You'll be asking yourself what sorcery is this when it boots in ~15 seconds or games where you used to have to wait about 15-20 seconds will load in less than 5 seconds. The other minor grip I have is I wished the theme of this board more closely resembled that of the MSI z690i. That board looks very nice. The silvery whiteness of this board can throw a big wrench into your black themed build.

Nonetheless, if you're on the fence about a Z series board this is the one to get, especially if you don't know how to UV. If you're on the fence between this and a B series board, MSI or Asus might be up your alley if you want to save some money so you can get a better gpu. Mind you, B boards cannot OC and UV'ing will have to be done manually and most of the guides are for the Asus B boards. Thanks for reading.

text: A helpful tool for usb powered devices is a Usb power monitor such as ACEIRMC ( usb power monitor). With this device you can tell the real output of the power suppy port , detect cable issues, defective port contacts, voltage & amperage inflows as battery regains power, detect slow battery charge or detect too high of amperage input for device you are trying to charge. It is something to consider for this fan and all your usb devices to keep them working well.

title: Needs more external pockets, wish it were smaller
text:
I use this for my primary travel computer bag. I wanted a replacement for my true underseat vertical two wheel rolling suitcase. I want one that is 2 inches narrower, two inches shorter, covered with externally accessible storage for an extension cord, power brick, phone, earbud case, chargers, back up battery, pens, mice, etc. That smaller frame should be accompanied by a 4 inch longer max pull handle length with 4 1.5 inch incremental locks for different height users.

I don't need the backpack option, but wish it were easier to mount to a larger rolling bag.

Finaly, the opening for the handle should not be open to bag contents. It should be water tight.

The bag was the closest I found but clearly not a match for my needs. I think the 19th century maxim, if you want something done right, you've got to do it yourself. Maybe I need to make a product that meets my needs.

Now I have used it for several trips an see it is sagging to the point it drags on the floor while rolling through an airport. I expect it to fail as a result and this disappoints me even more.

title: Easy install but plan on losing a fan if you have a current gen GPU
text:
Pros:
*Very easy to install in a O11 mini - literally takes 2 minutes
*Thumb screws only for install
*Leaves the bottom two PCIe slots open on a full size ATX mobo, which is nice
*Has slots in the bottom plate for more airflow to the GPU
*Overall is pretty secure and solid when installed properly, my GPU sits nice and level
*GPU fans sit at least 2 inches from the side glass (and thats with a 3 slot GPU), plenty of room for cooling. I have already confirmed no change in temps for my GPU.
*Bridge cable appears to be decent quality and is also flexible enough to move around a little.

Cons:
*If you have a current gen GPU (RTX 4000 series in particular) you are definitely going to lose the rear fan slot - look at my pic (thats an MSI gaming trio RTX 4070ti). The rear fan doesn't even come close to fitting with my GPU. I could install the fan on the outside of the case, that is actually an option and there is a slot to get the fan wires back through into the case, but I'm not sure yet if I want to do that or how it would look.
*One of the tabs on the left side of the mount (that interlocks with the case) is located where the mobo I/O shield is. This shouldn't be there because it actually interferes with installation. I had to flatten it out with pliers to get it to install correctly. I guess it would install right if you put this mount in BEFORE your motherboard install, but otherwise it doesn't.
*Its expensive for what it is. There are a lot of whole cases that don't cost this much. But if you have a O11 mini and you like the look, its worth having the one that is made specifically for this case.

NOTE: Depending on your GPU you may have to loosen the little screws holding the PCIe port down to the bottom plate, mine was too far back and the GPU wouldn't mount up properly. For a second I thought it wasn't going to fit, but luckily the port position can be slid forward/backward by a few millimeters as needed.

title: Was great for 3 months - Then microphones stops working if more than a few feet away from PC.
text:
I bought a set in early November, loved the fact that it connected to both my PCs so I didn't have to constantly switch settings, loved that I could walk around the house, even outside while still being able to unmute/mute myself and contribute to meetings.
It worked so well we bought another set for hubby the week after.
Well after 3 months of use his headset mic stopped working as soon as he walked 3ft away from his PC, works again as soon as close to the PC.
My set just started to do the same as well so it seems clearly to be a manufacturing issue.
The company asks for us to send video of us destroying the units in order to receive a money back to order from their website a set of similar or lower price.
1) we can't spend a week without headset while waiting for proof of destruction to be reviewed / approved
2) unwilling to buy another set from this vendor since that is 2 out 2 with the same defect.
In conclusion I do not commend.

title: Holy moly, this band is perfect!
text: I have been a fitbit user through more models than I can count. I am very hard on them because I do wear it 24/7. I bought these bands to replace the original and other after-market options that did not live up to my expectations. I wanted one that had a clasp, not the rubber push-through button, for the sake of stability. I wanted one that allowed my wrist to breathe while being sturdy enough to handle daily life with a toddler. I wanted one that looked professional enough to wear to work. I wanted one that didn't make my wrist itch or get red with irritation after use. And finally, I wanted one that didn't disconnect from my fitbit at the connection site (one of my biggest issues with multiple other bands). This band has checked every box!

title: Great earbuds for the price
text:
Recently my niece teen had lost/got stolen her Apple AirPods she had got for Christmas and she wasn‚Äôt getting another set. So I was glad I was able to get her these. She has been using them for a couple weeks now and loves them. She even liked the fit more than the ones she lost. I‚Äôm not saying they are better or anything like that. But she told me that she loved these and the fact that she could control right from the earbuds. She loved how easy it was to connect to her phone as well. She loved how they fit in her ears and had no complaints so far.

These are a decent price and definitely lower than Apple if not half the price. I can‚Äôt see myself paying top dollar for name brands for something so small that can be stolen so easily or lost. Especially when a teen owns them. So I would definitely recommend these at half the price of the name brand. Especially with something so small you can quickly lose it‚Äôs best to spend less for something just as good in my opinion.

title: Inexpensive USBa To USBc " charging" cable with limited 250Ma charge capability !
text:
This is a small gauge USBa to USBc charge only cable. Quality is Average and the connectors have plastic covers.
Using my USB tester , this cable had a voltage drop of 840Mv at 580 Ma load current. That's roughly 1.44 ohms for the cable. ( small gauge wire)

I was able to plug this cable into a high wattage quick charger, and the maximum amount of charge current I could get into a QC android device was 250 Ma ... Not going to charge very fast at that rate using this 33' cable.

title: Nice bluetooth headset.
text:
I had purchased another brand that while it worked well, the ear pieces didn't extend down far enough onto my ears. I felt like the top pad was pressuring the top of my head, while the ear pieces were too high on my ears.

I tried these and they fit much better. The extend far enough and the top padding doesn't feel like a rock.

Their sound is ok, but not fantastic. I use them for MS Teams meetings and they sound a bit hollow to me. The other issue is while the ear piece arms are metal, they seem a bit flimsy. I was hoping they would be a bit sturdier.

It come with a base that as two functions. It acts a a charger as well as a bluetooth connection. So if you have a computer without bluetooth, this can fill the void. The charging aspect works well but it is a bit of a pain to get the headphones into the base. It also comes with a bag case but it's a bit small for the headphones and the base and they barely fit.

Overall, if you are using these for meetings and voice, they are good, but I wouldn't expect good music quality of that's what you want to use them for.

text:

title: great affordable smart thermostat!
text: What's not to like.  $60, easy to install, easy to set up.  Just download Alexa app, scan QR code, and plug and chug. title: Nice Radio
text:
I bought this bc it looked rugged and has weather band and short band capabilities.
Once I received it however, it wasn't so rugged. It's all plastic and and "rugged" features are purely cosmetic.
I was honestly impressed with the sound. You don't expect the clarity and volume to come from this radio. I tried FM radio and I connected my phone via Bluetooth. It's definitely louder than my phone.
I tried using the short wave but I didn't have any luck. I have a list of all short band stations but I couldn't pick them up. The radio comes with a coil of wire to aid in better reception. However, my house is in a valley, so that may affect the reception.
The weather band works well. I was able to find the channels fairly quickly.
My only complaint is the price. After taxes it costs almost $50. If it wasn't so "plastic-ee", I think it would be reasonable.
Yes, it's a good music and weather radio, so if you don't mind paying for it, I recommend it.

title: Used to attach 4 4-up LEDs to a pin heatsink
text:
I used this product to attach some old 4-up Royal Blue LEDs to a pin heatsink.

More or less put small pea sized dabs where each LED was going to be placed, and then dropped the LEDs on them. I then put padding on the LEDs and about 10 lbs of weight on top of that and left it to cure for about 48 hours. I then cycled them a few times i.e. turn the LEDs on until they heated up / stabilized and then turned them off to cool down. That probably wasn't necessary but I figured I would err on the side of caution.

As you can see from the picture, I probably could have used just a little bit more adhesive since it didn't quite flow all the out on a couple of the corners. That's an issue on my part and not due to the adhesive though.

The LEDs have been running now over my indoor / hydroponic tomato plants for several weeks. The adhesive looks good and no problems. Heat transfer also looks good with the LEDs running nice and cool.

On a side note, it does say to use the entire tube once opened. I didn't need the full tube for the LEDs though. I just made sure that there wasn't any air in the tube and re-capped. I've used it since then on a number of other items e.g. heatsinks for open air Raspberry Pi boards.

title: Poor user interface, CarPlay often doesn't work
text:

title: A back zipper pocket for wallet and cellphone
text:
This backpack:
- Front size has 3 zipper pockets and 1 pocket (with 2 buckets); The thing that puzzles me is why are there 2 buckets in one of the front pockets. No zipper there, just a flap down pocket with 2 buckets. In my personal option, Velcro may be more ideal instead of buckets.

- Right and left size each has a pocket for water bottle or small umbrella. These pockets are not netted but sewed together by a solid fabric. This appears to be sturdier than netted one.

- Inside has 1 zipper pocket, laptop pocket, and 2 medium size pockets for notebooks/pens etc. The material separating the laptop pocket and the main compartment appears to be thinner than my other backpack. Not sure how much protection it can provide for the laptop.

- Back has a zipper pocket for wallet, cellphone, etc. This is by far my favorite part. This pocket is almost half the height of the backpack, thus, a lots of small value items can put here.

- Total of 7 buckets (2 in front, 4 on the side and 1 on the back) which add a little extra weight.

- The paddling on the strap seems a little thin when compared to my other backpacks. To me, this means less things should put in there to avoid heavy load on the shoulders.

I would recommend it for using as day hike, carry-on, elementary schoolers etc. Not so much for putting heavy stuff in it. Probably will not let my high schooler bring it to school since they have to carry more heavy books.

title: This thing is awesome
text: Love this device.  Very clever engineering.  Basically they are harnessing the same motor to either use as a vacuum or a little blower.  Comes with a bunch of little attachments of vary length that you can use to create a narrower and more powerful blast.  It absolutely is great for blowing out tiny spaces (inside dusty computers, etc), and has a wide attachment that can be used to inflate something like a pool float!  I don't have a technical measure of force, but it is significantly more powerful than a hair dryer (for example), and with the small sized nozzles it almost hurts to "air nozzle" your skin.  Even more useful to me is the vacuum feature, which I need for my cars (especially to get in between seats / etc.).  My only wish is that the vacuum attachment was a little longer, but it is long enough to work well for 98% of the carpet spots in my cars.  In summary, this is a great little product, love it!

title: Works fine.  Fits snugly in some keystone mounts
text: They get the job done and work fine.  I like how you don't need to buy a tool for a one time job.  Basically you strip back the cat5 or cat6 wire and wire using the  typology on the back of the keystone.  Once you get the wires organized then just push down the lever and it has a couple catches on each wire to ensure 100% connectivity.  The keystone plates that I picked up work but they are very snug and will take a bit of force to snap in place.  Overall they work fine and do the job.  Also a really great value over other cat6 keystone jacks plus toolless as well which was a big reason why I got these. If there is a problem with the wire all you need to do is simply lift the lever and redo the wire again and clamp it back down.  Very happy with these and easy to use.  Great value and price point for a 10 pack.

title: My old Anker Soundcores now look, sound, feel NEW AGAIN! The included tool makes it EZ!
text:
I sleep with my headphones so I'm hard on the ear pads and I needed a replacement as the white foam was showing so I purchased this set. I am happy with these new replacement ear pads! I would say almost 98% the exact same at the OEM. I am sure this product fits the Anker Life Q30 as stated in sellers description but also fits my Anker Soundcore phones I purchased at my local Big Box Store version with a different and hard to find model number but my model number can be located in very fine light print above the left ear phone ( I included a picture showing my model# A3029) . I found it to be an easy install and a perfect OEM style fit and finish! I found when using the included tool the process was not much more involved than replacing a cell phone case. You use the tool to snap the old pads off. I did not see any instructions but you have I think seven clips around each side, just work it a bit ( don't force as it is plastic clips ) but it comes right off and the new one snaps on with no tool needed.
My headphones now look, sound and feel new again! Happy with my purchase. I LOVE IT!

title: Another mislead photo of a chinamazon producr
text:
Where do I start? This is what's happening to Amazon lately, it's flooded with china junk with air brushed photos leaving you thinking you're getting a quality product and then you open the package just to be completely disappointed. It's not the most expensive bag I've bought my wife but it wasn't $35-45 which is exactly what the quality feels like. The dark lines between the seems that look like natural leather staining in the photos looks like someone spray painted them in real life. I mean it's almost a joke. My wife wanted this bag for her birthday and the second she pulled it out, she was completely shocked by the lack of quality in it especially for what it was paid for. A trend that is making me second guess about Amazon prime if this is the garbage they are going to approve vendors to sell on here. I feel sorry for others who passed the 30 day return window and now are stuck with a rip off "Gucci" named bag

I mean seriously, this isn't leather, it's rip off vinyl. I'm not buying these no name brand chinamazon garbage products anymore...

title: Wish it were "smarter"
text:
I love this thing for the convenience factor. I can charge my phone, watch, earbuds etc. and only use one outlet. The extended reach from the dedicated power cable has been indispensable recently; the location of outlets isn't always ideal, and this is especially true in hospitals where I spent the last week with my girlfriend. It reached the bed and gave us enough ports to charge both of our devices, and allowed us to keep family/friends updated while charging, as opposed to the phones being tethered to the wall.

The one gripe I have is that I wish it had smarter circuitry. As it is, if I want to Super Fast Charge my Samsung S22u, I can only have the single USB-C cable plugged in. It would be much more useful if the charger could detect whether or not the other ports were actively charging, and regulate power output based on that. I would love to be able to leave my watch charger cable plugged in and still have the super charging function. It would be an easy 5 stars if it had this feature!

title: Nice product, with one BIG flaw‚Ä¶
text: The case itself is nice. It‚Äôs sturdy and fits my iPad 9 really well, plus the print is pretty. The only reason I gave it 3 stars is the placement of the pencil holder loop. It‚Äôs on the left side and outside of the case, behind the front cover, so if I‚Äôm using my iPad and don‚Äôt need my pencil right then, this makes it REALLY awkward to put the pencil away. I end up either having to flip the cover closed or lean the iPad forward and try to sneak it over the top, both of which inevitably mess up what I have onscreen. I ended up buying another case with a built-in pencil holder. Basically, if you don‚Äôt have a pencil, then I highly recommend this case. If you do and use it a lot, get something else.

Great product, but I don't see enough of people talking about GOSUND!

title: Very Nicely Made Mount - Strong Magnet
text: Review for Magnetic Mount Base Stand Kit.  This mount exceeded my expectations.  It is a  very high quality piece of hardware.  I used this to mount a sports action video camera underneath a vehicle in order to locate a clunk in the suspension.  I had no problem finding places on the bottom of the vehicle flat enough to put the magnetic mount.  The base has very strong magnets in it that do a great job holding the mount and camera. The surface does not have to be perfectly flat in order for this mount to stick to it.  I found that if most of the surface under the magnetic base is relatively flat, the base will stick.  And this mount along with a video camera allowed me to pretty quickly find the loose shock absorber mounting bolt that was causing the clunk.

title: Decent case
text: The case is good as it serves it's purpose. I bought 3 different colors and they were all as pictured. My only complaint is that the silicone outer cover of the case comes off easily. My kids are having to have me fix it back on there often. It does not make the case any less protective; it's just a minor inconvenience. I would still recommend for the price.

title: Doesn't Work
text: This does not work at all. 3 desktops, 2 laptops, over a dozen different DP cables all from different companies and dates of purchase, 4 monitors (2 with GSync, 1 with Freesync, and 1 with nothing) and finally a projector. I was not able to pass through video with any combination using the above. Using another switch I borrowed from a friend from a name brand works perfectly fine with every combination above. I would suggest looking elsewhere.
